In the 22 midterm elections from 1934 -2018, the President's party has averaged a loss of 28 House seats. Similarly, from 1936-2018, near the midterms, six presidents have had approval ratings in the range of 40-45%--like Biden. In the House, presidents with approval between 40-45%, saw their party lose between 63 and 13 seats, with an average loss of 36 seats. There have been no instances of House seat gains for Presidents with approval as low as Biden’s.

The current generic ballot average from the five most recent quality polls of Likely Voters (Emerson, Rasmussen, The Economist, CBS News, and Harvard/Harris) gives the GOP a 5 point advantage. If that holds true, it would result in a House of Representatives divided 237-198 (Republicans/Democrats).

Multiple different resources (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/gop-house-2022/, CNN, and more) all agree that the House is likely to flip Republican. Multiple lines of thinking support this including history (most mid-terms flip various houses of congress) and concerns about the economy (high inflation).

The Economist's most recent model shows the House flipping to the Republicans by a most likely edge of 5-10 seats. This forecast aligns with the old adage of people vote their pocketbooks, which is especially relevant in the Fall, of 2022 given near record-high inflation, interest rates surging, and uncertainty about the availability of oil and gas (due to OPEC and the war in Ukraine). Huge uncertainty and fear usually favor the party out of power. Given this is the first mid-term election after the 2020 Presidential election, the incumbent party usually loses seats in the House (and often the Senate). The question, as yet unanswered is how many?

I'd guess the Republicans win this one narrowly. While the scales have been sliding more in the Democrats' favor amidst Roe v. Wade being overturned, loan forgiveness, etc., it still is likely now enough to counter-balance the lasting impact of economic downturn, inflation, and early low approval ratings for the current Democratic party-affiliated President. This, on top of the fact that it has been historically more likely that the opposing party gains momentum during midterms, combines historical data with informed speculation to formulate this forecast for the upcoming midterms.

The historical precedent of the party out of the White House picking up midterm seats is long established. Although Biden and the Democrats at the end of the session have a number of legislative accomplishments, it is doubtful in this polarized media landscape that such accomplishments will register with Republicans. The only way therefore that the Democrats can win a majority of house seats is for them to pick up seats in contested districts with large turnouts of their voters, which could happen due to issues like abortion.

While typically the opposing party to the president wins the midterm, the overturning of Roe has the potential to turn out incredible amounts of democratic voters, which makes this midterm one of the most heavily contested (in my opinion) elections in recent memory.

Trends in independent preferences in most competitive race seats are skewing hard to the right. Additionally the generic ballot issues under (important issues to vote) surveys consistently highlight a top 5 to 10 topics where Dems are all far in negative territory with in their "handling of" polling. Biden and other top of party favorability being so far into the negatives as well make any race that is even remotely competitive a likely R pick up. Many of these polling outfits are still measuring against D+5 or more weights/targets and in this past year alone over 1M people have left Dem registrations to either go Independent or republican. All these thing heavily favor an R turnout + enthusiasm + independent swing.

The reason that I believe that Democrats will maintain control of the US House of Representatives is due to the centrist policies and success of the Biden Administration. They have been largely popular and touched on swaths of the American people. The issues that we are faced with today are significantly challenging and the Administration is preparing the Democratic party to appeal to kitchen table conversations. In contrast, the Republican party is facing a messaging problem. They are scrambling to find a tag line that would give them the opportunity to pick up House seats and the rhetoric and unpopular policies of the conservative wing of the Republican party is crushing the more centrist approach to governing-- fracturing the party. With that being said, Republicans, a divided party, are unlikely to gain any traction in the mid-terms due to the fact that they have nothing to show for the last two years (save overturning Roe), their poor messaging, and inability to unite their base and bring in voters from the more centrist, moderate folds of the party.

Forbes writes: "Since 1946, the average number of seats lost by the president's party in the midterm elections is 46." I would have to look more into that distribution, but many scenarios exist where Republicans are generally not that popular with median voters and still capture just 10 seats or more - enough to sustain a sudden defection or two by any Congressman privately disgusted with Trumpian politics. The cyclical shifts in "enthusiasm" (outrage) easily translate into the necessary turnout advantage against the party of a POTUS whose popularity is below 50%, where Biden seems likely to remain with his "Honeymoon" period clearly over.

There are seismic issues yet to be decided. Congressional passage of voting rights legislation, the results from the January 6 Commission, and the initiation of criminal action against key political figures are all examples of events that are likely to influence the election that are yet to be determined. This will come much more into focus in the next three to four months.
maintaining current forecast

Given the narrow majority enjoyed by Democrats in the House, the tendency of the party out of the White House to gain seats in mid-term elections, and the likelihood that redistricting alone may net a few seats for the GOP, I rate a Republican takeover as “highly likely”.
Several factors point toward a Republican takeover of the House in the next election:

Historical base rate alone of midterm outcomes puts this >80% for President's party to lose. All evidence from Presidential approval rating & generic ballot polls support the historical trend. Beyond that, main variable will be economy which is probably not much improved in a year - even if inflation moderates, unlikely people feel great about the economic trajectory. Questions like redistricting and voting legislation matters on the margins but only could shift this by a few % points at most

This seems like a perfect time to challenge the conventional wisdom about non-Presidential results for several reasons. As a rule we have no maps to tell us what the new districts will look like, which will impact who the candidates are. It seems quite safe to assume that many of the yet-to-be proposed maps will be challenged in court and at least some of these challenges will prevail. Meanwhile, we've the extraordinary situation where the losing Presidential party doesn't ackowledge that it lose. So all we can is vent our partisan leanings and hope for the best.
Will depend heavily on whether there is passage of voting rights legislation in congress, which in turn would curb partisan gerrymandering and voter suppression.

The crowd odds of 21% for the Democrats to keep the House seems a bit low. Of course the party out of power usually wins and the base rate is extremely important in forecasting, so I might be committing the cardinal sin of base rate neglect, but I’m not sure 2022 will be an ordinary mid-term election with low turnout. Democratic voters are going to be well aware that Donald Trump will be running in 2024 and voting accordingly. At the same time, from the Republican perspective Trump will not be on the ballot in ’22, so their voters won’t have the same motivation to get out and vote. See for example the Georgia special election in which Jon Ossoff and Rev. Warnock won. That ordinarily should have been an easy victory for the party out of power. See also the VA gubernatorial race, which ordinarily might go to the Republican, who is a moderate and running during a time in which Biden’s popularity is underwater in an off-year election — except for the Trump factor motivating Democratic voters.
It doesn't look good for the Republicans at this point.
